KD Practicum 6.1

Classification Problems

Classification problems are solved using regression methods through generalization. Similarly though, there are several common steps that are utilized also by regression scenarios and in this exercise, you will explore them in conjunction of fitting a logistic function onto data. The basic steps that you will go through include tasks concerning:

  • Data pre-processing.
  • Exploring your data. There must be clear water between distributions of data points belonging to the classes you want to discriminate.
  • Creating a logistic model using a built-in function glm() from the stats package.
  • Testing several probability cut-offs before deciding on the best decision rule.
  • Generalizing your findings for unseen data.
  • Interpreting your findings and refine your model if necessary.

For this exercise, you need the functionality implemented by tidymodels, tidyverse and magrittr. broom and caret packages are optional.

Generalized linear models

Generalized linear model is an advanced statistical modelling technique, which includes linear Regression, logistic Regression, and Poisson Regression.

In this exercise, we will use the logistic function to predict the default state of a client by regressing onto credit card balance. Logistic regression does not make many of the key assumptions of linear regression and general linear models that are based on ordinary least squares algorithms particularly regarding linearity, normality, homoscedasticity, and measurement level.

Credit card dataset

We will use a simulated data set containing information on ten thousand customers, which is available for downloading from cloud.

  • Task 1: Load data from Default.csv into R. Are they ready to be modeled? If not, transform them into suitable format.

    #One-hot encoding

data$student <- ifelse(data$student == "Yes", 1,0) # One-hot encoding for student
#Converting to binary variables to factors
data %<>% mutate(default = as_factor(default))
data %<>% mutate(student = as_factor(student))
# Adding client IDs.
data %<>% mutate(ID = 1:length(data$default))
data %<>% select(ID, everything())

  • Task 2: Logistic regression works only if a modeled variable follows normal distribution and there is good separation of observations between classes (two in our case). Check if these conditions are fulfilled. Think about which statistical methods/functions are suitable to get this information.

    Answer: Separation of classes means that there can be a line drawn that splits data into two classes such that there are no miss-classified observations. This is not possible most of the time and our example is no exception. Lets print histograms and Q-Q plots that can shed some light into how many.

    It becomes clear that non-defaulters accumulate lower savings (mean: 804USD, standard error: 456USD) on their account compared to defaulters (mean: 1784USD , standard error: 341USD), and the distributions of both groups overlap. In addition, several other issues exist in our data with the following implications:

    • Fist, there are number of non-defaulters with 0 balance, meaning that they do not have any money left on their credit card account. This is a flaw that can be remedied by means of stratified sampling, should we model data as is.

    • Secondly, there are 9667 non-defaulters and 333 defaulters in the data set, making it unbalanced (although this is badly visible from the top right plot).

    • Third, no clear-line, or simple decision rule can be applied to correctly classify all observations and thus sacrifices have to be made.

Fit your first logistic regression model

Logistic regression is available upon calling the generalized linear model function glm() and then parametrizing the type of function to be fitted. The glm() function is available from the stats package that is automatically loaded when you start R.

  • Task 3: Fit a simple logistic regression function. Its up to you the glm() function is called directly or via the parsnip interface. Capture the model as an object. Check what type/class the object is. Use summary(), tidy(), str() and View() and other functions to investigate its content. Think about what additional operations can you do with it. Fit a regression line with parsnip and compare the results. Are they the same? If not, have the same function/package been used for the fitting?

    model <- glm(default ~ balance, data = data, family = binomial)

    Answer: glm() function returns a list, which is also an object of lm and glm type. This allows you subset it with rules you became familiar with in Practicum 2.1 through 2.3. To retrieve data from the object you can also use built-in functions from Practicum 4.2. Lets investigate how this works with our model:

    logR_model <- logistic_reg() %>% set_engine("glm")
logR_form_fit <- logR_model %>% fit(default ~ balance, data = data)

    Parsnip uses the same glm() function for fitting so there are no differences in terms of the objects content or the models parameters. However, remember that parsnip wraps the model object into another object containing metadata collected during the fitting. Hence, you have to go one level deeper to retrieve what information or data you want.

  • Task 4: Logistic regression is a classification algorithm only in combination with a decision rule that makes binary decisions based on predicted probabilities of the outcome. By default, the decision boundary is set to 50%, or 0.5 for no real reason.

    You are to test three different thresholds (e.g.1%, 50% and 70%, but they can be any you wish) to classify clients based on the probability of default. Each cut-off will split clients into four categories: defaulters, false-positive defaulters, false-negative defaulters and non-defaulters.

    Compare these predictions to the ground truth by means of confusion matrices and model performance metrics taught through the course. Your goal is to come up with the confusion matrices like the ones plotted below:

    Remember that the glm() function does not allow you to set custom thresholds, thus preventing you from making the predictions with a single function call.

    Instead, you have to find the way to leverage model information up to the point that confusion matrices can be generated. If you want to take this as a challenge, do not read the text below. It is possible that a package exists that does this for you and should you find one, please let me know.

    What you are about to do can be outlined with the following tasks:

    • First, use the existing model, or create a new one by fitting the logistic regression function onto data. Capture the model object.

    • For each balance value from the model object, retrieve the corresponding probability of default. The object contains fitted values. But what are these? Probabilities? Odds? Log odds? Find out.

    • If fitted values are not probabilities, find the way to convert them into probabilities. Since you are dealing with an S3 object, there must be a slew of helper functions to manipulate the encapsulated data. There are 10 000 records used for model training, so you are expected to land with 10 000 matched probabilities. One for each record.

      # Fitted values are log odds.
# To convert them into probabilities, run the following code:
model.probabilities <- predict(model, type = "response")

    • At the end of this pipeline, you will create confusion matrix to compare the ground truth to your predictions. Ground truth data are accessible through data$default , which is a vector of factors with two levels: 0 for not-default and 1 for default.

    • Hence, you need to come up with an equivalent vector of ones and zeros that are assigned from modeled probabilities. For example, for cut-off of 1%, the client will be treated as defaulter if the estimated probability of default is higher than 0.01 (and hence one-hot encoded as 1).

      glm.prediction <- rep(0, length(model.probabilities)) # create dummy output
glm.prediction[model.probabilities > .01] = 1 # one-hot encoding with given probability threshold.

    • You can use table() to generate the confusion matrix from these two vectors. As this is very dirty solution that does not come up with model performance metrics, you will use the confusionMatrix() function from the caret package. At the end of this quest you should see something like this:

      # library(caret)
confusionMatrix(as_factor(glm.prediction), as_factor(data$default), positive = "1")

Making predictions

Making predictions is a wee bit tricky, meaning that it is different for estimating probabilities for data not used for model training (aka new data), or whether you want to convert the new probabilities to get the matching balance.

  • Task 5: Practicum 7 will be more on this topic, but for now lets stay with predicting of probabilities for balance values of 1000, 1300, 1700, 2000, 3000.

    newData <- predict(model, newdata = tibble(balance=c(1000, 1300, 1700, 2000, 3000)),  type="response")
names(newData) <- c(1000, 1300, 1700, 2000, 3000)
newData
    ##        1000        1300        1700        2000        3000 
## 0.005752145 0.029234410 0.213631687 0.585769370 0.997115227

    Answer: We use the predict() function. Note that predict() has several dedicated versions that are selected upon receiving type of the model. Here, you run the predict.glm() function in the background, which is parametrized by type. The default type is on the scale of the linear predictors; the alternative "response" is on the scale of the response variable. Thus for a default binomial model the default predictions are of log-odds (probabilities on logit scale) and type = "response" gives the predicted probabilities.

  • Task 6: Convert the probabilities of default into classes using threshold of 0.6.

    classPrediction <- rep(0, length(newData))
classPrediction[newData > .6] = 1
names(classPrediction) <- c(1000, 1300, 1700, 2000, 3000)
classPrediction
    ## 1000 1300 1700 2000 3000 
##    0    0    0    0    1
